Notes: Autograph scores, as follows:. 1. ff.1-6. 'Seven Songs', words, F. Wyville Home; 1911-1912. Dedicated 'To my Mother'. The songs are 'The Morning of Love', begins 'Heart, my heart, what moves within you'; May 1911 (ff. 1v-2r); - 'Serenade', begins 'Now hither, my own heart's lover' (f. 2v); - 'Why bring the old loves back'; June 1911 (ff. 3r-3v); - 'Waiting', begins 'I rise up at day-break'; Sept. 1911 (ff. 4r-4v); - 'Forsaken', begins 'Lie still, forgotten and forsaken'; Feb. 1912 (ff. 4v-5r); - 'The Dewdrop', begins 'Open your leaves'; May 1912 (f. 5v); - 'The Pine-tree', begins 'On a naked peak'; October 1912 (f. 6r); 2. ff. 7-11v. Six Songs. The songs are 'To the Storm-wind', words, Percy Bysshe Shelley, begins 'Rough wind that moanest loud' (f. 7v); - 'Whenas in silks my Julia goes', words, Robert Herrick (f. 8r); - 'When I am dead', words, Christina Rossetti (ff. 8v-9r); - 'A Widow Bird', words, Shelley (f. 9v); - 'I fear thy kisses', words, Shelley (f. 10r); - 'Mary, I believed thee true', words, Sir Thomas Moore, crossed through in pencil (ff. 10v-11r); 3. ff. 12r-13v. 'Ich liebe dich' and 'A Maiden's Song', begins 'Never think of loving'; 4. ff. 14-17. 'March Morning' (words, F. Wyville Home), begins 'All the morning a throstle has sung'; 1916. 2 copies. Dated 14 May, 1916 (f. 14v). Published Novello, 1920; 5. ff. 18-18v. 'Absence' (words, anon); 1916. 2 copies. Dated 2 July 1916 (f. 17v). Published Novello & Co, 1920; 6. ff. 19-20v. 'Three Songs from 'Pot-Pourri' - a cycle by Isobel Scott-Bremner set to music for Voice and Orchestra by John Gerrard'; 1916. The songs are 'Pinks' (f. 19v); 'Lilies of the Valley' (f. 20r); 'Thyme' (f. 20v). Dated July-September 1916; 7. ff. 21-22v. 'Oh Mistress Mine', madrigal for 3 voices. Published W. Paxton & Co, 1922; 8. ff. 23-23v. 'My sweet sweeting', violin obbligato part. Dated Aug. 1924. Song published Oxford University Press, 1925; 9. ff. 24-25. 'A Lament', words, Shelley, begins 'O world! O life!'. For voice and piano. Dated October 1924 (f. 25); 10. ff. 26-27. 'Pretty Nan', ballad for voice and piano; n.d; 11. ff. 28v-29. 'The Crystal Spring', for voice and piano. Tune collected by Cecil J Sharp; n.d; 12. ff. 30-31. 'Sephestia's Song to her Child', words, Robert Greene, begins 'Weep not, my wanton'; n.d. For voice and piano; 13. ff. 32-33. 'Sweet Nymph, come to thy Lover', madrigal for three voices (SAT); n.d. With a sketch of Sephestia's song; 14. ff. 34-35v. 'Two Songs of Sorrow'; n.d. Comprises 'No more - ah! Never more', words, Shelley, for voice with a cello obbligato (ff.34-35); - 'Love's Secret, words, William Blake (f.35v); 15. ff. 36-36v. 'Tu me chamas', words Byron, begins 'You call me still your life'; n.d; 16. ff. 37-37v. 'A Fragment (from Becket)', words, Tennyson, begins 'Babble in bower'; n.d; 17. ff. 38-39v. 'Why so pale?', words Sir John Suckling; n.d; 18. ff. 40-40v. 'Sainte; (Transposed)', begins 'So calm and still'. Music by Maurice Ravel; words by MallarmÃ© in English translation; n.d; 19. ff. 41-54. Communion Service in C major, for unaccompanied voices (SATB); n.d; 20. ff. 55-73v. Communion Service in G major, for 6-part choir, organ and orchestra, incomplete. With Kyrie adapted from String Suite. Dated 1912, (f. 55)

Title: Six Notebooks used by Christina Rossetti for the inscription of fair copies of her poems; 17 June 1856-15 Feb. 1859 and 23 March 1861-11 June 1866. The notebooks are part of a series of seventeen covering the years 1842-1866, of which the others are Ashley MS. 1362 (1842-1845), nine in the Bodleian Library at Oxford, and one in the possession of Mrs Imogene Rossetti Dennis. The six comprised in Ashley MS. 1364 are all indexed, and contain extensive deletions and revisions made in pencil at various times by Christina and William Michael Rossetti when preparing the poems for publication. There are also pencil comments and revisions by Dante Gabriel Rossetti. Ashley Library Catalogue, ix, pp. 109-110
